White[nc]
Comment[W R14 and O17 are called "double birds" \("double flying swallows" in Chinese :-\) These two moves initiate a typical joseki in ancient Chinese games \(this joseki is still quite common today\).]
;
Black[pf]
Comment[Shi, in one of his book on Go theories, explained the direction of B #12.  If O16, after W N16, B O15, and W P17, W will be able to play K17, a good point since it salso presses B F17.  Therefore, the correct direction for B #12 isQ14, as Fan played here.]
;
White[pg]
;
Black[of]
;
White[qe]
;
Black[nd]
;
White[md]
Comment[This move can be also played at R16, then B should P17.  However, ancient players, who preferred "potentials", almost always played N16 here.  Today's players are probably in favor of R16 -- therefore, today, B would play R16 \(instead of O16\) to prevent W \(Note if W plays Q15 after B R16, B would give up P14 and Q14 and swallow W O17.  B would be better\).]
;
Black[oc]
;
White[nb]
;
Black[qd]
;
White[ob]
;
